questions_and_answers.question: How do I write a good lab conclusion in science?
questions_and_answers.answer: Verify that you’ve accomplished all the parts of your assignment so that you can properly address them in the conclusion. Take a few moments to make a list of what you’re supposed to demonstrate or learn in the experiment. 2. Revisit your introduction. To make sure your conclusion is consistent with the rest of your report, revisit your lab report’s introduction. This is a good tactic to help you brainstorm exactly what you’d like to say in your conclusion. 3. Use the RERUN method. Start mapping out the different elements of your conclusion by using the RERUN method. The RERUN method can be a useful structure overall for a short lab report, but it is especially useful for providing a conclusion to your report that reviews the experiment’s important components. RERUN stands for: : Restate the lab experiment by describing the assignment. : Explain the purpose of the lab experiment. What were you trying to figure out or discover? related_questions.question: How to write a good conclusion for a science experiment?
related_questions.title: When writing a conclusion you should:
list: briefly restate the purpose of the experiment (i.e. the question it was seeking to answer)
identify the main findings (i.e. the answer to the research question)
note the main limitations that are relevant to the interpretation of the results.

related_questions.question: What is an example of a conclusion in science?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: Restate the purpose: Briefly remind the reader of the original research question.
Summarize findings: Clearly state what the experiment showed or did not show.
Compare to hypothesis: Explain whether the results support or refute the hypothesis.
Discuss implications: Consider how the findings fit into the broader scientific context and what they might mean for future research or applications.
Acknowledge limitations: Be honest about any potential weaknesses or limitations of the study.
Suggest future research: Propose further studies that could build on the current findings.

Rejecting the null hypothesis: . Opens in new tabIn some cases, an experiment aims to disprove a null hypothesis. For example, if the original statement was that there is no difference in growth between plants under different light colors, and the results show a significant difference, the conclusion might be: "There is sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the color of light does affect plant growth."
Support for hypothesis: . Opens in new tabIf the results align with the initial prediction, the conclusion should clearly state that the hypothesis is supported.

Inconclusive results: . Opens in new tabSometimes, the results might not be clear-cut or might not provide strong evidence for or against the hypothesis. In such cases, the conclusion should acknowledge the inconclusive nature of the results and suggest further research.
